One way to reverse a linked list in-place is to traverse the list from the head to the tail, making a copy of each node as you go along. At the end of the traversal, the head of the original list should point to the last node in the new list, and the tail of the original list should point to the first node in the new list.

Here is an example implementation in C:
```C
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

struct node {
  int data;
  struct node *next;
};

struct node *reverse_list(struct node *head) {
  if (head == NULL) return head;
  struct node *new_head = NULL, *tmp;

  while (head != NULL) {
    tmp = head;
    head = head->next;
    new_head = (struct node*)malloc(sizeof(struct node));
    new_head->data = tmp->data;
    new_head->next = NULL;
    if (head != NULL) {
      tmp->next = new_head;
    } else {
      new_head->next = NULL;
    }
  }
  return new_head;
}

int main() {
  struct node *head = NULL;
  head = reverse_list(head);
  printf("Reversed linked list: ");
  while (head != NULL) {
    printf("%d ", head->data);
    head = head->next;
  }
  printf("\n");
  return 0;
}
```

Running the above code on the linked list `1 -> 2 -> 3 -> 4 -> NULL` will reverse it and print the result `4 -> 3 -> 2 -> 1 -> NULL`.

Go's implementation of a queue can be implemented using two stacks, as shown below:

```python
class Queue:
    def __init__(self):
        self.front = []
        self.back = []

    def enqueue(self, element):
        self.front.append(element)
        self.back.pop()

    def dequeue():
        return self.front.pop()

    def is_empty(self):
        return self.front == []

    def size(self):
        return len(self.front)
```

This implementation uses two stacks, front and back, to implement the queue. The front stack is used to keep track of the elements currently in the queue, while the back stack is used to maintain the LIFO (last-in, first-out) property of the queue. The enqueue and dequeue methods operate on these two stacks.

The enqueue method adds an element to the queue by pushing it onto the front stack and popping it from the back stack. The dequeue method removes an element from the queue by popping it from the front stack and returning it.

Finally, the is_empty, size, and is_full methods operate on the two stacks to determine if the queue is empty, its current size, or if it is full.

Here is a C# implementation of the quicksort algorithm:

```
using System;

class Program
{
    public static void Sort(int[] array)
    {
        if (array == null || array.Length <= 1)
            return;

        int p = array.Length / 2;
        int l = 0;
        int r = array.Length - 1;

        while (l < r)
        {
            // find the pivot index
            while (l < r && array[l] <= array[r])
                l++;
            while (l < r && array[r] < array[l])
                r--;

            if (l < r)
            {
                Swap(array, l, r);
                l++;
                r--;
            }
        }

        if (l < r)
            Sort(array, l, r);

        Swap(array, 0, p);
        return;
    }

    private static void Swap(int[] array, int i, int j)
    {
        var temp = array[i];
        array[i] = array[j];
        array[j] = temp;
    }
}
```

This function takes an unsorted array of integers as a parameter and sorts it using the quicksort algorithm. The function returns after sorting the array if it is already sorted, otherwise it recursively calls itself on the left and right subarrays until the entire array is sorted.

